HOUSE BILL No. 1348
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
utilities.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 8-1-46.1 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 46.1. Grease Control
5 Sec. 1. This chapter applies to the following:
6 (1) A commercial facility that discharges wastewater
7 containing fats, oils, or grease into a sewer system.
8 (2) A food establishment (as defined in IC 16-18-2-137).
9 (3) A mobile retail food establishment (as defined in
10 IC 16-18-2-239.3).
11 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "fats, oils, and grease" or "FOG"
12 means any organic substance derived from animal or vegetable
13 sources that may:
14 (1) solidify;
15 (2) congeal; or
16 (3) become viscous at ambient temperatures;
17 and can obstruct, accumulate, or interfere in a wastewater
EH 1348—LS 7011/DI 150

2
1 collection or a sewer system.
2 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "grease control equipment"
3 refers to the necessary combination of:
4 (1) grease interceptors; and
5 (2) grease traps;
6 to prevent fats, oils, grease, and food solids from being discharged
7 into a sewer system.
8 Sec. 4. As used in this chapter, "grease hauler" means a person
9 or company regulated and permitted by the Indiana department of
10 environmental management and that engages in the:
11 (1) collection;
12 (2) transport; or
13 (3) disposal;
14 of material removed from a grease trap or grease interceptor.
15 Sec. 5. As used in this chapter, "grease interceptor" means an
16 exterior or underground watertight receptacle that is designed to
17 intercept and retain:
18 (1) fats;
19 (2) oils;
20 (3) grease; and
21 (4) food solids;
22 from high volume wastewater flows before the wastewater is
23 discharged into a sewer system.
24 Sec. 6. As used in this chapter, "grease trap" means a watertight
25 tank designed to:
26 (1) intercept;
27 (2) congeal; and
28 (3) retain or remove;
29 fats, oils, and grease from wastewater before the wastewater is
30 discharged into a sewer system.
31 Sec. 7. As used in this chapter, "nonresidential onsite sewage
32 system" has the meaning set forth in IC 16-19-3.5-3.5.
33 Sec. 8. As used in this chapter, "properly sized" refers to the
34 sizing and configuration of a grease trap or grease interceptor in
35 accordance with:
36 (1) good engineering practice;
37 (2) state plumbing codes; and
38 (3) manufacturer specifications;
39 sufficient to prevent fats, oils, and grease from entering a sewer
40 system or a nonresidential onsite sewage system in quantities that
41 cause blockages, interference, or maintenance problems.
42 Sec. 9. As used in this chapter, "regulated entity" means a:
EH 1348—LS 7011/DI 150

3
1 (1) commercial facility that discharges wastewater containing
2 fats, oils, or grease into a sewer system;
3 (2) food establishment (as defined in IC 16-18-2-137); or
4 (3) mobile retail food establishment (as defined in
5 IC 16-18-2-239.3).
6 Sec. 10. As used in this chapter, "regulating authority" means
7 an entity that receives wastewater from a regulated entity.
8 Sec. 11. As used in this chapter, "sewer system" has the meaning
9 set forth in IC 36-9-22.5-3.
10 Sec. 12. As used in this chapter, "utility" means:
11 (1) a public utility (as defined in IC 8-1-2-1(a));
12 (2) a municipally owned utility (as defined in IC 8-1-2-1(h));
13 (3) a not-for-profit utility (as defined in IC 8-1-2-125(a));
14 (4) a cooperatively owned corporation;
15 (5) a conservancy district established under IC 14-33; or
16 (6) a regional district established under IC 13-26;
17 that provides sewage disposal service to the public.
18 Sec. 13. (a) A regulated entity shall install and operate properly
19 sized grease control equipment to prevent the discharge of
20 wastewater containing fats, oils, or grease in concentrations that
21 cause or contribute to:
22 (1) blockages;
23 (2) overflows; or
24 (3) interference;
25 in a sewer system.
26 (b) The regulated entity's grease control equipment shall be:
27 (1) designed; or
28 (2) approved;
29 by a licensed professional engineer under IC 25-31 or a
30 professional architect under IC 25-4.
31 (c) Subject to subsection (d), a regulated entity that
32 demonstrates through operational characteristics, inspection, and
33 sampling that the regulated entity does not generate fats, oils, or
34 grease in quantities requiring interception is:
35 (1) exempt from the requirements of this chapter; and
36 (2) not required to install grease control equipment.
37 (d) If a regulated entity's characteristics change and the
38 regulated entity begins to generate fats, oils, or grease in quantities
39 requiring interception, the regulated entity shall install grease
40 control equipment.
41 Sec. 14. A regulated entity's compliance with this chapter is
42 demonstrated through the installation, maintenance, and operation
EH 1348—LS 7011/DI 150

4
1 of grease control equipment in compliance with best practices that
2 meet applicable:
3 (1) state plumbing code requirements;
4 (2) manufacturer specifications;
5 (3) equipment performance standards; and
6 (4) sizing formulas adopted by the regulating authority.
7 Sec. 15. (a) A regulating authority charging additional sewer
8 rates or surcharges shall only charge the just and reasonable costs
9 to operate a FOG program.
10 (b) The regulating authority shall design the costs charged
11 under subsection (a) in a manner such that all costs required to
12 operate a FOG program are covered by the rate or surcharge paid
13 by the regulated entity.
14 Sec. 16. (a) The regulating authority shall evaluate a regulated
15 entity's compliance with this chapter based on the regulated
16 entity's actual discharge of FOG into a sewer system.
17 (b) A regulating authority shall consider the:
18 (1) size;
19 (2) products; and
20 (3) operational characteristics;
21 of each regulated entity when determining maintenance frequency,
22 inspection schedules, and rate classifications.
23 Sec. 17. (a) A utility or regulating authority may not:
24 (1) impose a blanket grease control equipment mandate; or
25 (2) require the:
26 (A) installation of a specific type;
27 (B) installation of a specific size; or
28 (C) specific location;
29 of a grease trap or grease interceptor if a regulated entity has the
30 properly sized and maintained grease control equipment that
31 prevents FOG discharges exceeding the allowable concentration.
32 (b) A regulating authority or utility may not require the
33 following:
34 (1) A specific type of grease control equipment.
35 (2) The specific placement of grease control equipment on the
36 property of a regulated entity, so long as the equipment is
37 placed outside of the utility's right-of-way of easement and
38 upstream of a utility's system.
39 Sec. 18. (a) Before construction or a major renovation of a
40 regulated entity, the owner of the regulated entity or the owner's
41 agent shall submit the proposed grease control equipment design
42 to the applicable regulating authority for review before
EH 1348—LS 7011/DI 150

5
1 installation.
2 (b) Upon receiving the grease control equipment design
3 described in subsection (a), the regulating authority shall review
4 the proposed design and provide:
5 (1) a written approval;
6 (2) a written denial; or
7 (3) modification recommendations;
8 based on performance standards under this chapter within sixty
9 (60) days.
10 (c) A regulating authority shall coordinate with the appropriate:
11 (1) building and zoning authority;
12 (2) plumbing permit authorities; or
13 (3) utility;
14 to ensure the regulated entity receives consistent direction before
15 construction.
16 (d) A regulating authority that determines a regulated entity's
17 proposed:
18 (1) grease control equipment design; or
19 (2) maintenance plan;
20 does not meet the performance standard shall provide a written
21 explanation to the regulated entity.
22 Sec. 19. A regulating authority or utility may not require the
23 regulated entity to retrofit or replace grease control equipment
24 unless the regulated entity's FOG discharge exceeds the allowable
25 concentration at least two (2) times within a thirty (30) day period.
26 Sec. 20. A regulating authority and utility shall permit a
27 regulated entity to comply with this chapter through alternative
28 grease control equipment or maintenance protocols approved by
29 the regulating authority where installation of an exterior grease
30 interceptor is impractical due to:
31 (1) the available space;
32 (2) the structure; or
33 (3) other site constraints.
34 Sec. 21. A regulating authority shall maintain a FOG control
35 and maintenance program.
36 Sec. 22. (a) A regulated entity shall do the following:
37 (1) Install, operate, and maintain grease control equipment
38 designed to prevent fats, oils, and grease from entering the
39 wastewater system or a nonresidential onsite sewage system.
40 (2) Ensure that grease control equipment is properly sized
41 and maintained in compliance with section 13 of this chapter.
42 (3) Maintain records that include the:
EH 1348—LS 7011/DI 150

6
1 (A) date of each haul;
2 (B) volume of FOG removed; and
3 (C) grease hauler's name.
4 (b) A regulated entity shall maintain all records under this
5 section for two (2) years.
6 Sec. 23. A grease hauler shall do the following:
7 (1) Take before and after time stamped photographs of each
8 service of a regulated entity.
9 (2) Maintain the time stamped photographs and share the
10 time stamped photographs with the Indiana department of
11 environmental management and regulating authority if
12 requested by the Indiana department of environmental
13 management or regulating authority.
14 (3) Maintain records showing that the total volume of FOG
15 pumped from a regulated entity matches the total disposed of
16 by the grease hauler.
17 (4) Provide documentation or an invoice to a regulated entity
18 after service is completed with the following information:
19 (A) The date of the haul.
20 (B) The volume of FOG removed.
21 (C) The grease hauler's name.
22 SECTION 2. IC 13-11-2-242, AS AMENDED BY P.L.19-2019,
23 SECTION 1, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
24 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 242. "Unit", for purposes of:
25 (1) section 148(c) of this chapter;
26 (2) IC 13-18-12-7.5;
27 (2) (3) IC 13-20-17.5;
28 (3) (4) IC 13-20-20;
29 (4) (5) IC 13-21-14-3; and
30 (5) (6) IC 13-23;
31 has the meaning set forth in IC 36-1-2-23.
32 SECTION 3. IC 13-18-12-7.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
33 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
34 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 7.5. (a) As used in this section,
35 "septage" means human excreta, wastewater, scum, sludge, and
36 other content introduced through incidental or accidental seepage
37 that is removed from domestic septic tanks, holding tanks, privies,
38 seepage pits, cesspools, compost toilets, or portable sanitary units.
39 (b) As used in this section, "septage management vehicle"
40 means a vehicle that is:
41 (1) used for:
42 (A) the removal of septage from holding tanks or sewage
EH 1348—LS 7011/DI 150

7
1 disposal systems; and
2 (B) the transportation of the septage to wastewater
3 treatment plants or other facilities for treatment,
4 temporary storage, or disposal; and
5 (2) subject to regulation under this chapter and 327 IAC 7.1.
6 (c) A wastewater treatment plant that has allowed for the
7 disposal of septage on or after January 1, 2023, shall continue to
8 allow for the disposal of septage that is picked up from within the
9 unit where the wastewater treatment plant is located or a
10 neighboring unit to the wastewater treatment plant. However, a
11 wastewater treatment plant need not accept septage if the
12 wastewater treatment plant is not:
13 (1) designed to receive;
14 (2) permitted to receive; or
15 (3) operationally capable of receiving;
16 septage in accordance with a permit approved by the department.
17 (d) If a septage hauler believes that a wastewater treatment
18 plant is not accepting septage in violation of subsection (c), the
19 septage hauler may submit a written request to the department to
20 determine whether the wastewater treatment plant must accept
21 septage.
22 (e) After consulting with the septage hauler and the owner of the
23 wastewater treatment plant, the department shall issue:
24 (1) a determination; and
25 (2) if applicable, an order requiring the wastewater treatment
26 plant to accept septage.
27 (f) A determination or order issued by the department under
28 this section is subject to review under IC 4-21.5.
29 (g) A unit accepting septage from a septage management vehicle
30 may charge a fair and reasonable fee.
31 (h) Nothing in this section shall be construed to require a
32 wastewater treatment facility to accept septage in a manner that:
33 (1) conflicts with its National Pollutant Discharge Elimination
34 System permit or other department issued permit;
35 (2) causes or contributes to a treatment process upset or
36 permit violation; or
37 (3) necessitates capital improvements or operational changes
38 without full cost recovery.
EH 1348—LS 7011/DI 150

